GOALKEEPER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS DUFRESNE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Belgium came as close to the last-ditch hockey strategy of pulling its goalie 
as you will ever see in soccer when its goalkeeper, Michel Preud'homme, left 
the net to join his team's comeback cause late in the second half of Saturday's 
game against Germany. 
</P>
<P>
 With Belgium trailing, 3-2, Preud'homme sprinted downfield to take part in the 
offense at the German end. He nearly made head contact with a corner kick 
delivered by teammate Josip Weber. 
</P>
<P>
 "I had nothing to lose," Preud'homme said. "If I can help the team tie the 
game, 3-3, then we can go to extra time. That was my intention." CHRIS DUFRESNE 
</P>
