<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOLLYWOOD PARK; LONGSHOT MAKES TRIP WORTH IT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB MIESZERSKI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Jerry Bailey's trip to California wasn't a waste of time after all. 
</P>
<P>
 Three races after Arcangues finished last in the Gold Cup, Bailey rode R Friar 
Tuck to a $47.20 upset in the $163,600 Affirmed Handicap. 
</P>
<P>
 Riding the 3-year-old gelding for the first time, Bailey sat off the pace 
early, moved up four-wide approaching the quarter-pole to join the leaders, 
then went on to win by three-quarters of a length over Pollock's Luck in 1:49 
for the 1 1/8 miles. 
</P>
<P>
 Bred in Utah by owner S. David Plummer, one of the country's leading breeders 
of quarter horses, R Friar Tuck showed nothing in his first four starts but has 
won three of his last five. 
</P>
<P>
 Wild Invader was third, a half-length behind Pollock's Luck and it was another 
four back to Argolid, the 9-10 favorite. 
</P>
<P>
 The day's other stakes race, the $108,400 Triple Bend Handicap, also provided 
some consolation for Arcangues' trainer, Richard Mandella. 
</P>
<P>
 Memo, one of the country's top sprinters, won by 2 3/4 lengths in a track 
record 1:20 2/5 for the seven furlongs. Fifty Six Ina Row set the old record of 
1:20 4/5 in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Hollywood Wildcat, who remained unbeaten on the turf with a victory in the 
Gamely Handicap on June 12, is the 7-5 morning-line favorite in the $323,400 
Beverly Hills Handicap at Hollywood Park today. 
</P>
<P>
 Returning after a layoff of about four months, Hollywood Wildcat dropped back 
to last at one point in the Gamely, then took off late and won by 2 1/4 lengths 
for her third grass victory. Eddie Delahoussaye will again ride the 4-year-old 
Kris S. filly, who will carry 124 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
 Flawlessly, the co-highweight, is the 8-5 second choice as she tries to 
rebound from her first defeat in seven starts on the Hollywood Park turf 
course. Horse Racing Notes 
</P>
<P>
 The other entrants in the Beverly Hills, which will be run at 1 1/8 miles, are 
Mz. Zill Bear, Corrazona, Potridee, Empress Club and Zoonaqua. . . . There is a 
two-day carryover in the Pick Six of $233,768.43. . . . Hollywood Park will 
simulcast the $300,000 Arlington Classic today between the fourth and fifth 
races. Corey Nakatani will ride Eagle Eyed for trainer Bobby Frankel in the 1 
1/8-mile turf race and Chris Antley will be aboard Jersey Derby winner Zuno 
Star for trainer Mark Hennig. 
</P>
<P>
 Seven horses were entered Saturday morning for Monday's $218,000 American 
Handicap at 1 1/8 miles on the turf. From the rail out, the entrants include 
Gothland, Semillon, Silver Wizard, Johann Quatz, Blues Traveller, Portico and 
Furiously. . . . Favored Work The Crowd won the $100,000 Pucker Up Stakes 
Saturday at Arlington. Turk Passer beat 1993 Kentucky Derby winner Sea Hero by 
2 3/4 lengths in winning the $150,000 Bowling Green Handicap at Belmont Park. 
Fraise, the 6-5 favorite, was another neck back in third in the field of six in 
the 1 3/8-mile turf race. . . . Hyroglyphic scored a wire-to-wire victory in 
the $116,000 Bashford Manor Stakes at Churchill Downs. Boone's Mill, part of 
the favored Wayne Lukas-trained entry, was six lengths back in second in the 
race for 2-year-olds. 
</P>
